WATFORD manager, Roy Hodgson has ruled William Troost-Ekong out for the “foreseeable future” after the defender strained his muscle. Hodgson announced on Friday ahead of the Hornets’ game against Arsenal at Vicarage Road. “It’s a muscle strain, the same with Troost-Ekong,” said Hodgson of Senegal star, Ismaila Sarr.   ‘We have taken steps to reposition Lobi Stars’     Nigeria v Ghana: Ighalo’s inclusion raises doubt     WC playoff: Ndidi predicts tough Ghana game   “It’s going to keep them both out of the equation for the foreseeable future, but I don’t know how long exactly. “It’s not a minor thing, it’s not a knock, both have muscle strains, and that can take anything from a week to four weeks to recover from.” Nigeria earlier announced Troost-Ekong, a mainstay of the team and assistant captain of the Super Eagles as one of the invited players. Should he be declared missing out of the game as a result of the injury, Alanyaspor’s Chidozie Awaziem has been listed as the standby defender on the provisional squad.